@Yanyan-Wang 

I chose to explicitly list the event names  for each type (node, edge, combo etc) to make the code maintenance a bit easier?
- if a developer wants to know all event names for specific entity (node/graph/combo), they can quickly go directly to the list
- adding new types might be easier mentally, the person only needs to go directly to the entity they are interested in

Common events like `click`, `mouseenter` etc that could be grouped together in one type and then merged to avoid some duplication, but I think some duplication for simplicity might be better. 
**1. What do you think?**
- imagine I am a contributor or developer using G6 and I use my  code editor (VS Code) to jump to the definition of a Node's event's, I can see everything in one place, without needing to reference other types (like a common event type).


The list when updated will automatically update this type below
```ts
// template literal types: https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/template-literal-types.html
export type NodeEventType = `node:${NodeInteractionEvent}`;
export type EdgeEventType = `edge:${EdgeInteractionEvent}`;
export type ComboEventType = `combo:${ComboInteractionEvent}`;
export type CanvasEventType = `canvas:${ComboInteractionEvent}`;
export type GraphTimingEventType = GraphTimingEvents;
export type MobileInteractionEventType = MobileInteractionEvent;
export type G6EventName = NodeEventType | EdgeEventType | ComboEventType | CanvasInteractionEvent | GraphTimingEventType | MobileInteractionEventType;
```

